node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Kate | That Debt Free Life on August 15, 2021. May be an image of one or more people and text that says 'TRUST THE PROCESS'.

node.text:
Hello friends! It’s been a while! I’ve taken an unexpected break from posting, and I’ve gotta admit, life untethered to a phone is quite beautiful. 

I’m not sure what the future holds for this account. Whether I’ll return to posting daily, or as the moment strikes, or not at all. 

As I suspected, after I left the practice of law back in March, my interest in this account started to dwindle. I wasn’t miserable in my life anymore, and without that misery, I wasn’t desperately motivated to obsess over my finances. I didn’t need financial independence to escape the hell-on-earth life I’d created for myself. I’m finally happy—working a job I actually enjoy and that pays beautifully. 

So, I just don’t know. But I had a moment today and came across a quote in one of my notebooks I thought I’d share with anyone who’s climbing that mountain, trying to dig themselves out of debt or accomplish any task that, at times, feels impossible: 

It’s from Ruth Soukup’s book Do It Scared, and it goes like this: 

“Trust the process and understand that it’s supposed to be hard. If it were easy, everyone would be doing it. Remember, the greatest accomplishments are the ones you have to work for.”

You’ve got this. 💗

node.text:
I get asked all the time how to begin this debt free journey. This is as simple as it gets right here.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
I also have lots of tips for paying down debt and getting started on my saved stories under Resources. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
And, a free guide that explains all the different things my husband and I did to pay off six figures worth of debt. You can check that out by clicking the link in my profile and heading to Free Guide: Pay Off Your Debt Faster Than You Thought Possible. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Oh, and my favorite debt payoff strategy is the debt snowball. Find out all about how to pay off debt with that strategy (or with the debt avalanche) by hitting up the blog. ⁣⁣

⁣The biggest mistake I see people make with debt payoff is believing they won’t be able to do it and not getting started sooner as a result. ⁣
⁣
If you haven’t begun aggressively paying off your debt, what’s stopping you? Don’t let the false belief that you can’t do it be the reason. Trust me, you CAN. ⁣

node.text:
Time for another #onethingwednesday — one simple thing you can do today to improve your financial health. 

Today’s tip? Download (and use!) a personal finance app. 

Some of my favorites: Envelopes Budget Manager, Charlie Finance, Personal Capital, Paidback. I use them all! 

What are some of your faves?

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Kate | That Debt Free Life on June 21, 2021. May be an image of text that says '7:05 PM How much have I spent on fuel in 2021? You spent $674 on Gas this year. How much did I spend on fuel in 2020? You spent $510 on Gas between Jan 1, 2020 and Dec 31, 2020.'.

node.text:
Blah. The year isn’t even half over yet and I’ve already spent more on gasoline this year than I did in ALL of 2020. 

I think this is true for two reasons: gas prices are much higher this year, and at the end of March, I started working in the office twice a week. 

I’m not kidding when I say I saved literally thousands between gasoline and tolls by working from home all last year. 

My new company is making noises that we’ll all be expected to go back to the office full time in September. 😭😭😭 I am not ready for it! Nor am I ready for all the associated increased expenses with having to commute to the office daily. So gross. 

What’s your work situation look like? If you’re working, are you working from home? Back in the office? 

App is Charlie Finance, btw, and I love it!

node.text:
I’ve been falling off the posting wagon lately. I always check in on my goals mid-month, and I totally forgot to this month. So here’s your monthly reminder to check in on those goals and re-adjust the plan as necessary. 

Here’s what I wanted to accomplish in June: 

1️⃣✅ Increase 401(k) contributions by 1%. Goal met! I’ve been doing this monthly for the last 3 months, and I think I’ve finally found my sweet spot.

2️⃣✅ Start a Back-to-School sinking fund. Goal complete! I added $150 to this fund in June and will add to it throughout the summer. It’ll cover school supplies and new clothes/shoes for the upcoming school year for my 5th grader. 

3️⃣✅ Invest $3,000. Goal met! I got paid yesterday, and immediately sent $707.69 to my HSA, which was enough to bring my total June investing to $3,000 even. 🙌🏻 

How’s your June going? What did you want to accomplish this month? Still plenty of time!!

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Kate | That Debt Free Life on June 17, 2021. May be an image of one or more people and text that says '$ One Thung Wedkesday ONE THING YOU CAN DO TODAY TO IMPROVE YOUR FINANCIAL HEALTH: Call your cell phone provider and negotiate your plan. @THATDEBTFREELIFE'.

node.text:
I know it’s not Wednesday and time got away from me yesterday, but I still wanted to give you one simple task you can do this week to improve your financial health! 

I did this last year and lowered by bill by a LOT—by simply asking. 

I just called my cell phone provider and said “I’ve been a customer for 12 years. What can we do today to make sure it’ll be 13?” 😜 

And they gave me a significant discount on my bill! 

Remember the answer is always no unless you ask! 

Have you ever tried something like this?!
#onethingwednesday

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Kate | That Debt Free Life on June 16, 2021. May be an image of one or more people and text that says 'tdfl ΚΑΤΕ KINGSLEY THAT DEBT FREE LIFE So many of us are guilty of mindless consumption-buying things we think will bring happiness to our lives or make us a better/prettier/more valuable/more likeable human being. We fall prey to the advertising ploys of companies whose sole purpose is to convince us to spend, spend, ,spend-often against our best interest. @THATDEBTFREELIFE WWW.LIVINGTHATDEBTFREELIFE.COM'.

node.text:
This is how they get you. Companies are counting on the fact that you aren’t paying attention to your money. That you’re just mindlessly or impulsively spending away, hopefully on some product that they’ve spent millions advertising to you. 

Don’t fall for it! 

Make a plan for your money! And spend according to that plan. 

My favorite way to do this is by making a zero-based budget for every paycheck I get. I make a plan for every penny and spend accordingly. Now, it’s not perfect every time, but it does prevent me from getting to the end of the month and saying things like “How did I spend $600 eating out this month?” Or, “How did I spend $450 shopping?”

Seriously, making a zero based budget for every paycheck is the one piece of financial advice that’s really helped me get control of my finances and manage my money well. I still do it to this day—even after being debt free for over a year and a half. 

Are you spending your money with intention?

node.text:
We recently received a property tax refund of almost $1,000!! Whoop! 

While it would be fun to splurge with this money and treat ourselves, my husband has had a few high medical bills lately and this will come in super handy to pay them off. 

I always like to have a smart plan for unexpected money/windfalls so I don’t waste the blessing. 

What would you do with an extra $1,000 right now?

Photo by Kate | That Debt Free Life on June 10, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'THE TRIPLE TAX ADVANTAGES OF AN HSA Contributions are tax-free, reducing taxable income. Growth within the account is tax-free. Qualified withdrawals (those used for health-related expenses) are tax free. @thatdebtfreelife'.

node.text:
Three reasons to love your health savings account (“HSA”)!!!

Unlike a Flexible Spending Account (“FSA”), the money in your HSA rolls over year to year. It isn’t “use it or lose it.” 

But the best part? You can invest the money inside your HSA and use it as another tax-advantaged retirement account. 

At age 65, your HSA functions just like a traditional IRA. Meaning you can withdraw the money from your HSA without penalties (you still have to pay taxes) for non-medical expenses at age 65+. Ummm, yes, please! 

This is why it’s my goal to max out my 2021 HSA up to the family limit this year. And why I have no intent of touching it for actual medical expenses in the meantime. My plan is to cash flow all medical expenses, invest in my HSA like mad, and let that money pile up for retirement. 

And the other cool thing? I’m saving all my medical receipts, so if I ever *did* want to withdraw $ from my HSA, I’ll be able to. There’s no time limit on when you can reimburse yourself from your HSA! Meaning, you can reimburse yourself for expenses years after they occurred. Cool, huh? 

Have I convinced you yet?! HSAs for the win!!!
